Example 8

Given $n(U) = 40$, $n(A) = 24$, $n(B) = 27$ and $n(A \cap B) = 13$, find:

(a) $n(A \cup B)$

(b) $n(A \cap B')$.

Solution:

We see that $b = 13$ {as $n(A \cap B) = 13$}

$a + b = 24$ {as $n(A) = 24$}

$b + c = 27$ {as $n(B) = 27$}

$a + b + c + d = 40$ {as $n(U) = 40$}

Solving these, $b = 13$ $\therefore$ $a = 11$, $c = 14$, $d = 2$

(a) $n(A \cup B) = a + b + c = 38$

(b) $n(A \cap B') = a = 11$
